Title: Arthritis

Overview:
- Arthritis is a condition that causes inflammation, pain, and stiffness in the joints.
- It can affect one or multiple joints and is more common with increasing age.
- The most common types are osteoarthritis (due to wear and tear) and rheumatoid arthritis (an autoimmune condition).
- Symptoms may develop gradually or suddenly depending on the type.
- Proper management can help reduce pain and improve mobility.

Common Symptoms:
- Joint pain that may worsen with movement.
- Stiffness in joints, especially in the morning or after rest.
- Swelling around the affected joints.
- Reduced range of motion or difficulty moving joints.
- Warmth or redness over the joint area.
- Weakness in muscles around the joints.
- Pain that increases after physical activity.

Risk Factors:
- Aging, which increases wear and tear on joints.
- Family history of arthritis.
- Previous joint injuries.
- Obesity, which puts extra pressure on joints.
- Autoimmune conditions affecting the body.
- Lack of physical activity.
- Repetitive joint stress from certain occupations.

Basic Home Diagnosis (Preliminary Checks):
- Observe joint pain, stiffness, or swelling in specific areas.
- Check if stiffness is worse in the morning or after inactivity.
- Monitor how pain changes with movement or rest.
- Identify joints affected such as knees, hands, or hips.
- Track duration and frequency of symptoms.
- Note any difficulty in performing daily activities.
- If symptoms persist or worsen, consult a healthcare professional.

Management and Prevention:
- Maintain a healthy weight to reduce stress on joints.
- Engage in regular low-impact exercises like walking or stretching.
- Use hot or cold compresses to relieve pain and swelling.
- Eat a balanced diet to support joint health.
- Avoid excessive strain or overuse of joints.
- Practice good posture and body mechanics.
- Take medications only if prescribed by a doctor.
- Stay physically active to maintain flexibility and strength.

When to Seek Medical Help:
- Persistent joint pain lasting several weeks.
- Severe swelling or redness in joints.
- Difficulty moving joints or loss of function.
- Sudden increase in pain or stiffness.
- Joint deformity or unusual changes.
- Symptoms interfering with daily activities.

